Trimming Reads with BBDuk

Background

When raw sequencing files are downloaded, they still contain adapter sequences at the ends of each read. While necessary for sequencing, they contribute no usable information and therefore serve only to contaminate the reads. In addition, read quality can vary along its length, often requiring the read ends to be trimmed in order to remove untrustworthy base calls.

Although the adapters differ between protocols, a relatively small number of protocols are used for the majority of sequencing runs, meaning that it is often not necessary to know the exact adapter sequence.

BBMap is a suite of tools designed to process sequencing data. One of the tools, bbduk, can perform a number ofquality filtering steps. We will use it to do three things:

  1. Automatically find and remove a range of common adapter sequences and other similar contaminants such as PhiX sequences (a type of control). Custom adapter sequences can also be inputted if needed.
  2. Quality trim and filter reads
  3. Remove any low-entropy reads (i.e.repetitive sequences)

Identify adapters

The list of built-in bbduk adapters can be found in the resources folder of the tool. The default collection is here and will be the link referred to throughout the below tutorial.

Unfortunately, not all publicly-available datasets have adapter information available. If present, adapter information can usually be found in the Methods section of the original manuscript. Check the supplementary data to see if there are any supplementary methods available, which may provide additional information. Sometimes the FastQC output will predict what adapter sequences are present under Overrepresented sequences (see Validate with FastQC). Two examples are shown below:

Straightforward example

Wallen et. al (2022): Metagenomics of Parkinsons disease implicates the gut microbiome in multiple disease mechanisms

Methods > DNA isolation, library preparation, next-generation sequencing: The sequencing libraries were prepared by using the Illumina Nextera XT transposase system.

Methods > Bioinformatic processing of sequences > QC of sequences: QC of sequence reads was performed using BBDuk and BBSplit. In the first step of QC, BBDuk was used to remove Nextera XT adapter and PhiX genome contamination, and quality trim and filter sequences.

Here, we can see that the adapters for the Nextera XT transposase system are available in the list of built-in bbduk adapters. When running the tool, we can simply set ref=adapters or ref=adapters.fa.

Tricky example

Metcalfe-Roach et. al (2024): Metagenomic Analysis Reveals LargeScale Disruptions of the Gut Microbiome in Parkinsons Disease

Here the Methods section in the manuscript says shotgun metagenomic sequencing was performed on the Illumina NovaSeq platform, but does not explicitly include library prep information.

In the Supplementary Methods, it specifies that libraries were barcoded with unique dual indexes using xGen DNA Library Prep EZ and xGen Normalase module kits from Integrated DNA Technologies (CA, USA). A search of the built-in adapters shows that it does not include key words such as xGen, and so the kit documentation must be checked to identify the adapter sequences.

Checking the xGen DNA Library Prep EZ documentation, the adapter sequences for unique dual indexes (UDI) are listed in the Appendix:

If we search these adapter sequences against the built-in bbduk adapters, we can see that the areas to the left and right of the underlined indexes do indeed match some of the other built-in adapters; unfortunately, however, the indexes themselves are different. Clicking on the Index Sequences Master List at the bottom of the appendix and following the instructions in the Indexing Overview tab, we find the full list of indexes on the xGen Normalase UDI Primers tab.

It is then trivial, if somewhat annoying, to build a list of all adapter sequences that can then be fed into bbduk. For example, the full sequences can be assembled in Excel (as shown below) and then pasted into a text file. Format the text file similarly to the list of built-in bbduk adapters and upload it to your Compute Canada directory.

**Note: degenerate sequences can now also be addressed by the tool. See Matching degenerate sequences such as primers in the docs.

Running BBDuk

The main function used for trimming reads is bbduk, which is part of the BBMap module. While BBMap is available as a module on Compute Canada, the repository of built-in adapters will not be visible for inspection. The repo can be manually searched (or downloaded) at the GitHub link here if needed.

Ideally, both the forward and reverse reads will be inputted. If using only the forward reads, delete the in2 and out2 parameters.

Because the tool is computationally intensive, it will be run as a submitted job. Navigate to the desired directory and open a new job script by writing nano run_bbduk.sh into the terminal. Paste in the following script, changing names and file paths as needed.

#!/bin/bash

#SBATCH --account=def-bfinlay   # Change bfinlay to your professor's username
#SBATCH --time=06:00:00      # Adjust time as needed
#SBATCH --cpus-per-task=10
#SBATCH --mem=15G 

# Load the dependencies
module load StdEnv/2023 bbmap/39.06 java/21.0.1

# Make the output directories
mkdir bbduk_out
mkdir bbduk_out/stats

# Trim the reads to remove (built-in) adapters & PhiX sequences AND
# to remove any bases under a certain quality score.
# The following is adapted from Wallen et. al (2022), as their samples are being used as an example above. Their supplementary code can be found in their paper.
bbduk.sh \
 # Specify fwd and rev reads
 in=path/to/fwd/reads/file_1.fastq.gz \
 in2=path/to/rev/reads/file_2.fastq.gz \
 # Specify where the trimmed files will be saved
 out=bbduk_out/file_1.fastq.gz \
 out2=bbduk_out/file_2.fastq.gz \
 outm=bbduk_out/file_removed.fastq.gz \
 # The stats output will describe the sequences that were trimmed
 stats=bbduk_out/stats/file_stats.txt \
 # tpe, fwd and rev trimmed to same length
 # tbo, BBmerge implementation for additional trimming (pairwise reads only)
 # qtrim=rl, right and left trimming; trimq, trim to this quality score
 # maq=25, throw out any reads with a mean quality score <25 (calculated after trimming)
 # minlen, remove sequences below n length
 # ref, list of possible adapters/contaminants to trim (these are built in)
 tpe tbo qtrim=rl trimq=25 maq=25 minlen=50 ref=adapters,phix \
 # bbduk uses half available memory by default, this uses all available
 -Xmx15g

The stats output files can be inspected to ensure that the reads are being trimmed/filtered as expected. The following shows the reads that were trimmed using the above code on sample SRR19065040_1.fastq.gz. As expected, we can see that 99% of the trimmed sequences matched the Nextera Transposase adapter sequence, which was used to prep the library.

Once bbduk has been run and it has been verified that the adapters are being trimmed as expected, the low complexity reads can be removed.

Validate with FastQC

FastQC can recognize overrepresented sequences, including adapter sequences. If the adapter sequences are generic, it may be able to provide the likely name of the adapter. For example, the FastQC of a raw file gave the following information under Overrepresented sequences:

The original paper did not list any information related to adapters, and so BBDuk was run using ref=adapters,phix. By running FastQC on the BBDuk output, we can see that this overrepresented sequence was indeed removed, thus validating the BBDuk output:
